		"body": "Desktop: Fixes #14763: Add settings search\r\n\r\nProblem\r\nThe settings screen in the desktop application lacked a search functionality, making it difficult for users to find specific settings, especially as the number of options grows. This required users to manually scroll through all the sections to find what they were looking for.\r\n\r\nSolution\r\nThis pull request introduces a search bar on the configuration screen to allow users to quickly filter and find settings.\r\n\r\nThe implementation includes:\r\n\r\n- A new search input field added to the ConfigScreen component.\r\n- A filtering function that filters settings based on the user's search query. The search is case-insensitive and matches against the setting's label, description, and key.\r\n- Sections that have no matching settings are hidden from view.\r\n\r\nThis change improves the user experience by making the settings screen more accessible and efficient to use.\r\n\r\n\r\nTest Plan\r\nAutomated unit tests have been added in to cover the filtering logic. These tests verify:\r\n\r\n- Correct filtering by label, description, and key.\r\n- Case-insensitive search.\r\n- Handling of empty queries and no-match scenarios.\r\n- Correct behavior with multiple matching settings across different sections.\r\n\r\n\r\nManual Testing:\r\n\r\n- Open the settings screen.\r\n- Use the new search bar to search for a setting by its name (e.g., \"theme\"). Verify that only relevant settings are displayed.\r\n- Search for a setting by its description (e.g., \"application theme\"). Verify the correct setting is shown.\r\n- Search using a partial keyword (e.g., \"font\"). Verify all settings related to fonts are displayed.\r\n- Clear the search bar and verify that all settings are visible again.\r\n- Enter a search query that has no matches (e.g., \"nonexistent-setting\"). Verify that a \"no results\" message is displayed.",
